            <div type="edition">
            <ab>
                <lb n="1"/>
                <persName>
                    <name type="praenomen" key="Marci"><expan><abbr>M</abbr><ex>arci</ex></expan></name>
                    <name type="gentilicium" key="Holconius">Holconii</name>
                    <name type="cognomen" key="Rufus">Rufus</name>
                </persName>
                <lb n="2"/>et
                <persName>
                    <name type="cognomen" key="Celer">Celer</name>
                </persName> cryptam, tri
                <lb n="3" break="no"/>bunalia, theatrum
                <expan><abbr>s</abbr><ex>ua</ex></expan>
                <expan><abbr>p</abbr><ex>ecunia</ex></expan>.
            </ab></div>
            
            <div type="translation">
            <p>Marcus Holconius Rufus and Marcus Holconius Celer (built) the crypt, the platforms, (and) the theater at their own expense.</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>The text reproduces that of CIL 10.833 and 834, two copies of (apparently) single-line inscriptions, reconstituted from multiple fragments found throughout the large theater at Pompeii and now in the Naples Museum. This granite inscription, with the text disposed over three lines, seems to be an original creation, possibly inspired in part by the fragment, CIL 10.835, of which the second line (of three) happens to be broken at the left before "bunal(ia)" of ". . . tri]bunalia". The balanced ordination and skillfully carved lettering of the Harvard inscription must be credited to the modern stone-cutter.</p></div>
            

